<p><b>Kim Eric Drexler</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1955-04-25"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="04-25"><a href="/wiki/April_25" title="April 25">April 25</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1955" title="1955">1955</a></span> in <a href="/wiki/Oakland,_California" title="Oakland, California">Oakland, California</a>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> engineer best known for popularizing the potential of <a href="/wiki/Molecular_nanotechnology" title="Molecular nanotechnology">molecular nanotechnology</a> (MNT), from the 1970s and 1980s. His 1991 doctoral thesis at <a href="/wiki/MIT" title="MIT" class="mw-redirect">MIT</a> was revised and published as the book <i>"<a href="http://www.e-drexler.com/d/06/00/Nanosystems/toc.html" class="external text" title="http://www.e-drexler.com/d/06/00/Nanosystems/toc.html" rel="nofollow">Nanosystems Molecular Machinery Manufacturing and Computation</a>"</i> (1992), which received the <a href="/wiki/Association_of_American_Publishers" title="Association of American Publishers">Association of American Publishers</a> award for Best Computer Science Book of 1992. He also coined the term <a href="/wiki/Grey_goo" title="Grey goo">grey goo</a>.</p>
